ECON 4345 - Health Economics
An introduction to health economics, which uses economic analysis to
study the structure and performance of the healthcare industry. The
topics covered include individual behavior and the demand for
healthcare, the production and costs of healthcare, information and health
insurance markets, and the basic institutional features of the healthcare
system in the United States. Finally, the economic analysis and
institutional knowledge of the healthcare system are used to evaluate the
performance of the healthcare system and analyze healthcare policy
reforms.
Prerequisite: ECON 2302.
